Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST NODE STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Uniform AST node for every Solidity construct. node_type carries the
SOL_* discriminant; value holds a string lexeme for leaf nodes
(identifiers, literals, operator symbols on binary expressions); children
is an ordered ListCore of sub-nodes; metadata is a flat ListCore of
alternating key, value pairs at even/odd indices respectively. Flat
encoding avoids per-node dictionary overhead while preserving lookup by
key.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte slots in declaration order:
node_type@0, value@8, children@16, metadata@24.
@End Implementation

Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    children as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PARSER STATE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state: a ListCore handle of tokens, a 0-based cursor position,
and the pre-computed token count. Length is cached at construction so
end-of-stream tests stay O(1) rather than calling list_length on every
check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three 8-byte slots: tokens@0, position@8, length@16.
@End Implementation

Type called "Parser":
    tokens as Integer
    position as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN PARSER ENTRY POINTS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-call pipeline driver: lex then parse. Exposed as a top-level entry
point for callers who only have raw source text and do not want to manage
the lexer or parser separately.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_solidity_source" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tokens be proc solidity_lex from SolidityLexer with source
    Let parser be proc create_parser from tokens
    Return proc parse_program from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parser constructor. Stores the token list, sets position to 0, and caches
the token-list length. Caching length here ensures every later check
against parser.length is a struct field read rather than a list_length
call.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_parser" takes tokens as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser be a value of type Parser with
        tokens as tokens,
        position as 0,
        length as proc list_length from ListCore with tokens

    Return parser
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PROGRAM PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level production: builds a SOL_PROGRAM node and accumulates every
successful top-level declaration as a child. Skipped declarations
(parse_top_level_declaration returns 0) are not added — they were
already consumed and discarded as recovery tokens.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_program" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let program be proc create_node with SOL_PROGRAM, ""

    Note: Parse top-level declarations
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Let decl be proc parse_top_level_declaration from parser
        If decl is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with program, decl
        End If
    End While

    Return program
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for top-level Solidity constructs. Matches the leading
token against pragma, import, contract (including the abstract-contract
shape that prefixes `abstract`), interface, library, using, and error
definitions. Any other token is consumed silently as a recovery measure
to keep parsing forward-moving.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_top_level_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Pragma directive
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PRAGMA:
        Return proc parse_pragma from parser
    End If

    Note: Import directive
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IMPORT:
        Return proc parse_import from parser
    End If

    Note: Contract
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONTRACT:
        Return proc parse_contract from parser
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT:
        Return proc parse_contract from parser
    End If

    Note: Interface
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INTERFACE:
        Return proc parse_interface from parser
    End If

    Note: Library
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LIBRARY:
        Return proc parse_library from parser
    End If

    Note: Using directive
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_USING:
        Return proc parse_using from parser
    End If

    Note: Error definition
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ERROR:
        Return proc parse_error_definition from parser
    End If

    Note: Skip unknown tokens
    proc advance from parser
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PRAGMA PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `pragma <name> <free-form-value>;` directives — most commonly
`pragma solidity ^0.8.0`. The value section is free-form (lexer breaks it
into multiple tokens) so we concatenate token text until the terminating
semicolon. The reconstructed value is stored as "value" metadata.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_pragma" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PRAGMA

    Let pragma_type be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let pragma_node be proc create_node with SOL_PRAGMA, pragma_type

    Note: Parse pragma value (e.g., "^0.8.0" for solidity version)
    Let value be ""
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
            proc set_metadata with pragma_node, "value", value
            Return pragma_node
        End If

        Let current be proc current_token from parser
        Let token_value be proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current
        Set value to proc string_concat from StringCore with value, token_value
        proc advance from parser
    End While

    proc set_metadata with pragma_node, "value", value
    Return pragma_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: IMPORT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `import "<path>" [as <alias>];`. Records the path string and
optional alias as metadata. The minimal subset of Solidity import syntax
is supported (no symbol-list imports or wildcard imports yet — these can
be added without breaking the AST shape because they ride entirely on
metadata).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_import" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IMPORT

    Let import_node be proc create_node with SOL_IMPORT, ""

    Note: Parse import path (string literal)
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Let path be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRING
        proc set_metadata with import_node, "path", path

        Note: Check for "as" alias
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_AS:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_AS
            Let alias be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
            proc set_metadata with import_node, "alias", alias
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return import_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CONTRACT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `[abstract] contract <Name> [is Base1, Base2, ...] { ... }`. The
abstract prefix is recorded as a metadata flag rather than a separate
node type so contracts and abstract contracts share AST consumers
downstream. Inheritance bases come from parse_inheritance_list and are
attached as a "bases" metadata list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Optionally consumes `abstract`, then `contract`, captures the identifier
as the node value, optionally consumes an `is`-prefixed inheritance list,
then loops parse_contract_member between the braces. Each member becomes
a direct child of the contract node.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_contract" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse abstract modifier if present
    Let is_abstract be 0
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ABSTRACT
        Set is_abstract to 1
    End If

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONTRACT

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let contract_node be proc create_node with SOL_CONTRACT, name

    Note: Store abstract flag
    If is_abstract is equal to 1:
        proc set_metadata with contract_node, "abstract", "true"
    End If

    Note: Parse inheritance (is Base1, Base2)
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IS
        Let bases be proc parse_inheritance_list from parser
        proc set_metadata with contract_node, "bases", bases
    End If

    Note: Parse contract body
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return contract_node
        End If

        Let member be proc parse_contract_member from parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with contract_node, member
        End If
    End While

    Return contract_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses one or more comma-separated identifier base names following an
`is` keyword. Returns a ListCore of name strings rather than ASTNode
objects because bases are name-references only and need no further
structure at this layer. Requires at least one base identifier — callers
guard with TOKEN_IS.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_inheritance_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let bases be proc list_create from ListCore

    Let first_base be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    proc list_append from ListCore with bases, first_base

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        Let base be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        proc list_append from ListCore with bases, base
    End While

    Return bases
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for declarations valid inside a contract body. Recognises
using, struct, enum, event, error, modifier, constructor, fallback,
receive, function — and falls through to parse_state_variable for
anything else, since state variables have no leading keyword (they begin
with a type token).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_contract_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Using directive
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_USING:
        Return proc parse_using from parser
    End If

    Note: Struct definition
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRUCT:
        Return proc parse_struct from parser
    End If

    Note: Enum definition
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ENUM:
        Return proc parse_enum from parser
    End If

    Note: Event definition
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EVENT:
        Return proc parse_event from parser
    End If

    Note: Error definition
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ERROR:
        Return proc parse_error_definition from parser
    End If

    Note: Modifier definition
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MODIFIER:
        Return proc parse_modifier from parser
    End If

    Note: Constructor
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR:
        Return proc parse_constructor from parser
    End If

    Note: Fallback function
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FALLBACK:
        Return proc parse_fallback from parser
    End If

    Note: Receive function
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RECEIVE:
        Return proc parse_receive from parser
    End If

    Note: Function
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_function from parser
    End If

    Note: State variable (starts with type or visibility)
    Return proc parse_state_variable from parser
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: INTERFACE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `interface <Name> [is Base, ...] { ... }`. Same shape as contract
but uses parse_interface_member which restricts permitted declarations to
function/event/error signatures (interfaces cannot have state variables
or implementations).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_interface" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INTERFACE

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let interface_node be proc create_node with SOL_INTERFACE, name

    Note: Parse inheritance
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IS
        Let bases be proc parse_inheritance_list from parser
        proc set_metadata with interface_node, "bases", bases
    End If

    Note: Parse interface body
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return interface_node
        End If

        Let member be proc parse_interface_member from parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with interface_node, member
        End If
    End While

    Return interface_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Restricted dispatch table for interface members: only events, functions
(without bodies — parse_function_body returns 0 on semicolon), and error
declarations. Unknown leading tokens are advanced past and yield 0.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_interface_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Interfaces only have function declarations and events
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EVENT:
        Return proc parse_event from parser
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_function from parser
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ERROR:
        Return proc parse_error_definition from parser
    End If

    proc advance from parser
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: LIBRARY PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `library <Name> { ... }`. Libraries are stateless code-bearing
containers — they reuse parse_contract_member because the set of valid
declarations matches contracts (minus state variables semantically; but
the parser does not enforce that here — later HIR validation does).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_library" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LIBRARY

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let library_node be proc create_node with SOL_LIBRARY, name

    Note: Parse library body
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return library_node
        End If

        Let member be proc parse_contract_member from parser
        If member is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with library_node, member
        End If
    End While

    Return library_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: USING DIRECTIVE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `using <Library> for <Type|*>;`. The library name lives as the
node value and the target type lives as "target" metadata. `*` is
accepted as the wildcard target (binds the library's methods to all
types). The keyword `for` is matched by lexeme rather than by token type
because the lexer treats it as a generic identifier in this context.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_using" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_USING

    Let library_name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let using_node be proc create_node with SOL_USING, library_name

    proc consume_keyword with parser, "for"

    Note: Parse target type (can be "*" or specific type)
    Let current be proc current_token from parser
    Let target_type be proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current
    proc advance from parser
    proc set_metadata with using_node, "target", target_type

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return using_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STRUCT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `struct <Name> { type field1; type field2; ... }`. Fields are
parsed by parse_struct_field and attached as ordered children. Struct
fields share the SOL_PARAMETER node type with function parameters and
event parameters because they carry the same `type name` shape.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_struct" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRUCT

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let struct_node be proc create_node with SOL_STRUCT, name

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    Note: Parse struct fields
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return struct_node
        End If

        Let field be proc parse_struct_field from parser
        If field is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with struct_node, field
        End If
    End While

    Return struct_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `<type> <name>;` for a single struct field. The type node lives
in "type" metadata rather than as a child because consumers want
type/name separation at lookup time. Trailing semicolon is required.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_struct_field" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_node be proc parse_type from parser
    Let field_name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

    Let field be proc create_node with SOL_PARAMETER, field_name
    proc set_metadata with field, "type", type_node

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return field
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ENUM PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `enum <Name> { Value1, Value2, ... }`. Enum values are bare
identifiers (no associated data), stored as a "values" metadata list of
strings. Trailing commas are tolerated because the loop consumes a comma
opportunistically after each value without requiring one.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_enum" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ENUM

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let enum_node be proc create_node with SOL_ENUM, name

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    Note: Parse enum values
    Let values be proc list_create from ListCore

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            proc set_metadata with enum_node, "values", values
            Return enum_node
        End If

        Let value be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        proc list_append from ListCore with values, value

        Note: Check for comma
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    proc set_metadata with enum_node, "values", values
    Return enum_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EVENT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `event <Name>(parameters) [anonymous];`. Event parameters can
have an `indexed` modifier between the type and the optional name (see
parse_event_parameter) — events use up to 3 indexed parameters for log
topics in the EVM. Anonymous events skip the first topic and are flagged
in metadata.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_event" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EVENT

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let event_node be proc create_node with SOL_EVENT, name

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Note: Parse event parameters
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

            Note: Check for anonymous modifier
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ANONYMOUS:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ANONYMOUS
                proc set_metadata with event_node, "anonymous", "true"
            End If

            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
            Return event_node
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_event_parameter from parser
        If param is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with event_node, param
        End If

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    Return event_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses one event parameter: `<type> [indexed] [<name>]`. Unlike function
parameters, the name is optional (event logs don't need it). The
`indexed` flag is stored as "indexed" metadata so HIR translation can
emit the parameter into the appropriate EVM log topic slot.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_event_parameter" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_node be proc parse_type from parser

    Note: Check for indexed modifier
    Let is_indexed be 0
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INDEXED:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INDEXED
        Set is_indexed to 1
    End If

    Note: Parameter name is optional in events
    Let param_name be ""
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set param_name to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    Let param be proc create_node with SOL_PARAMETER, param_name
    proc set_metadata with param, "type", type_node

    If is_indexed is equal to 1:
        proc set_metadata with param, "indexed", "true"
    End If

    Return param
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR DEFINITION PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `error <Name>(parameters);` — a Solidity 0.8.4+ custom error
declaration. Errors are like events but throw rather than log. Parameters
use the regular parse_parameter routine (no `indexed` modifier permitted)
so structure matches function parameter lists.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_error_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ERROR

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let error_node be proc create_node with SOL_ERROR, name

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Note: Parse error parameters
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
            Return error_node
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
        If param is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with error_node, param
        End If

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    Return error_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MODIFIER PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `modifier <Name>[(parameters)] [virtual|override] { body }`.
Modifiers are decorators applied to functions and run with access to the
function arguments and the magic `_;` placeholder. Parameter list is
optional (zero-arg modifiers can omit the parens entirely); virtual /
override come from parse_function_modifiers.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_modifier" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MODIFIER

    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let modifier_node be proc create_node with SOL_MODIFIER, name

    Note: Parse parameters if present
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

        While proc not_at_end from parser:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                Let body be proc parse_block from parser
                proc add_child with modifier_node, body
                Return modifier_node
            End If

            Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
            If param is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with modifier_node, param
            End If

            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Parse virtual/override modifiers
    proc parse_function_modifiers with parser, modifier_node

    Set body to proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with modifier_node, body
    Return modifier_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: FUNCTION PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `function [<name>](parameters) [modifiers...] [returns (...)] {
body }` or a signature ending in `;` for interfaces. Function name is
optional because anonymous functions appear as type expressions in
Solidity 0.6+. Visibility, mutability, virtual/override, and return-type
parsing are delegated to parse_function_tail.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION

    Note: Function name (can be empty for fallback)
    Let name be ""
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set name to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    Let function_node be proc create_node with SOL_FUNCTION, name

    Note: Parse parameters
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
            proc parse_function_tail with parser, function_node
            Return function_node
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
        If param is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with function_node, param
        End If

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    Return function_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shared tail logic for function-like declarations after the parameter
list: visibility/mutability/virtual/override modifiers, optional
`returns (...)` clause, then either a body block or a semicolon. Split
out from parse_function because constructor/fallback/receive reuse parts
of it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls parse_function_modifiers to gobble modifier keywords. If `returns`
follows, parses a comma-separated return parameter list into a fresh
ListCore and stores it as "returns" metadata, then dispatches to
parse_function_body. If no `returns`, falls through directly to
parse_function_body.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_tail" takes parser as Integer, function_node as Integer:
    Note: Parse visibility, mutability, modifiers
    proc parse_function_modifiers with parser, function_node

    Note: Parse return type if present
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURNS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURNS
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

        Let return_types be proc list_create from ListCore

        While proc not_at_end from parser:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                proc set_metadata with function_node, "returns", return_types
                Let body_parsed be proc parse_function_body with parser, function_node
                Return
            End If

            Let return_param be proc parse_parameter from parser
            If return_param is not equal to 0:
                proc list_append from ListCore with return_types, return_param
            End If

            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Parse function body
    proc parse_function_body with parser, function_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Collects any number of leading modifier keywords (visibility, mutability,
inheritance flags) in any order. Solidity's grammar is intentionally
permissive here — `function foo() public view virtual returns ...` and
`function foo() view public ...` are both valid. We loop until we see a
non-modifier token, then stop without consuming it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops checking for each of public/private/internal/external/pure/view/
payable/virtual/override; on hit, consumes the token and appends the
modifier name string to the modifiers list. First non-matching token
breaks the loop and finalises modifiers metadata.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_modifiers" takes parser as Integer, function_node as Integer:
    Let modifiers be proc list_create from ListCore

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Note: Visibility modifiers
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC
            proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "public"
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PRIVATE:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PRIVATE
                proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "private"
            Otherwise:
                If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INTERNAL:
                    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INTERNAL
                    proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "internal"
                Otherwise:
                    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EXTERNAL:
                        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EXTERNAL
                        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "external"
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: State mutability modifiers
                        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PURE:
                            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PURE
                            proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "pure"
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_VIEW:
                                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_VIEW
                                proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "view"
                            Otherwise:
                                If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PAYABLE:
                                    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PAYABLE
                                    proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "payable"
                                Otherwise:
                                    Note: Virtual and override
                                    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_VIRTUAL:
                                        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_VIRTUAL
                                        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "virtual"
                                    Otherwise:
                                        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_OVERRIDE:
                                            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_OVERRIDE
                                            proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "override"
                                        Otherwise:
                                            Note: No more modifiers
                                            proc set_metadata with function_node, "modifiers", modifiers
                                            Return
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc set_metadata with function_node, "modifiers", modifiers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches on what follows the modifier/returns clause: a `;` means
this is an abstract or interface declaration (return 0, no body
attached); anything else is parsed as a brace block and attached as a
child. Return value indicates body presence so callers can record
abstractness if useful.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_function_body" takes parser as Integer, function_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Function can end with semicolon (interface) or have a body
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return 0
    End If

    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with function_node, body
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTOR PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `constructor(parameters) [modifiers...] { body }`. Constructors
have a fixed name ("constructor") rather than a user-supplied
identifier. They share parameter parsing with regular functions but
always require a body — Solidity does not allow a semicolon-only
constructor declaration.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_constructor" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR

    Let constructor_node be proc create_node with SOL_CONSTRUCTOR, "constructor"

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Note: Parse parameters
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
            proc parse_function_modifiers with parser, constructor_node
            Let body be proc parse_block from parser
            proc add_child with constructor_node, body
            Return constructor_node
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
        If param is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with constructor_node, param
        End If

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    Return constructor_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: FALLBACK AND RECEIVE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `fallback() [modifiers] [returns (...)] { body }`. The fallback
function fires when a contract call matches no selector. As of Solidity
0.6, fallback takes no parameters but may return bytes. We still pre-
allocate the parameter list parsing to keep code shape consistent with
parse_function — the parentheses are always empty here.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_fallback" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FALLBACK

    Let fallback_node be proc create_node with SOL_FALLBACK, "fallback"

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    proc parse_function_modifiers with parser, fallback_node

    Note: Parse returns if present
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURNS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURNS
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

        Let return_types be proc list_create from ListCore

        While proc not_at_end from parser:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                proc set_metadata with fallback_node, "returns", return_types
                Let body be proc parse_block from parser
                proc add_child with fallback_node, body
                Return fallback_node
            End If

            Let return_param be proc parse_parameter from parser
            If return_param is not equal to 0:
                proc list_append from ListCore with return_types, return_param
            End If

            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Set body to proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with fallback_node, body
    Return fallback_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `receive() external payable { body }`. The receive function
fires on plain ether transfers (no calldata). Solidity requires receive
to be `external payable` and to take no parameters or returns — the
parser does not enforce these constraints here; parse_function_modifiers
captures whatever the source provides for later validation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_receive" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RECEIVE

    Let receive_node be proc create_node with SOL_RECEIVE, "receive"

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    proc parse_function_modifiers with parser, receive_node

    Let body be proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with receive_node, body
    Return receive_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATE VARIABLE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses `<type> [visibility] [constant|immutable] <name> [= initializer];`.
State variables have no leading keyword in Solidity, so this is the
fallback in parse_contract_member. Visibility and storage qualifiers may
appear in any order before the name and are stored as a "modifiers"
metadata list. The initializer is parsed as an expression and held in
"initializer" metadata.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses the type via parse_type, then loops over visibility/constant/
immutable tokens (each appears at most once but accepted in any order
via separate While loops to keep grammar permissive). Captures the
identifier as the node value, attaches type and modifiers metadata,
parses an optional `= expression`, and consumes the terminating `;`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_state_variable" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_node be proc parse_type from parser

    Note: Parse visibility and modifiers
    Let modifiers be proc list_create from ListCore

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PUBLIC
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "public"
    End While

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PRIVATE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PRIVATE
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "private"
    End While

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INTERNAL:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INTERNAL
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "internal"
    End While

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONSTANT:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONSTANT
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "constant"
    End While

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IMMUTABLE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IMMUTABLE
        proc list_append from ListCore with modifiers, "immutable"
    End While

    Let var_name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    Let var_node be proc create_node with SOL_STATE_VARIABLE, var_name

    proc set_metadata with var_node, "type", type_node
    proc set_metadata with var_node, "modifiers", modifiers

    Note: Parse initializer if present
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN
        Let init_expr be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc set_metadata with var_node, "initializer", init_expr
    End If

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return var_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PARAMETER PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses one function/error/struct parameter: `<type> [memory|storage|
calldata] [<name>]`. Data-location qualifiers (memory/storage/calldata)
are mandatory for reference types in external/public functions but the
parser doesn't enforce that here — it just captures whatever was given as
"storage" metadata. Name is optional (anonymous parameters are legal in
abstract function signatures).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_parameter" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_node be proc parse_type from parser

    Note: Parse storage location if present
    Let storage_location be ""
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MEMORY:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MEMORY
        Set storage_location to "memory"
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STORAGE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STORAGE
        Set storage_location to "storage"
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CALLDATA:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CALLDATA
        Set storage_location to "calldata"
    End If

    Note: Parameter name is optional
    Let param_name be ""
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set param_name to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    End If

    Let param be proc create_node with SOL_PARAMETER, param_name
    proc set_metadata with param, "type", type_node

    Let storage_len be proc string_length from StringCore with storage_location
    If storage_len is greater than 0:
        proc set_metadata with param, "storage", storage_location
    End If

    Return param
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TYPE PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recognises every Solidity type expression at this layer: elementary
types (bool/uintN/intN/address[ payable]/bytesN/string), mapping types
(delegated to parse_mapping_type), and user-defined types with optional
array brackets. Array brackets nest left-to-right so `T[][3]` parses as
"fixed-size 3 of dynamic T" — matching Solidity's right-most-is-outer
convention.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequential keyword checks dispatched on token type. For sized integer/
bytes variants (uint8, uint16, ..., uintN) the token's value field
carries the precise width, so we copy it verbatim into the node value.
Array bracket handling wraps the current type_node in a new
SOL_ARRAY_TYPE on each `[size]` suffix, with size captured as a string
("" for dynamic arrays).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Elementary types
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_BOOL:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_BOOL
        Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, "bool"
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_UINT:
        Let current be proc current_token from parser
        Let type_name be proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_UINT
        Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, type_name
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INT:
        Set current to proc current_token from parser
        Set type_name to proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INT
        Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, type_name
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ADDRESS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ADDRESS

        Note: Check for "payable" modifier
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PAYABLE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PAYABLE
            Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, "address payable"
        End If

        Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, "address"
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_BYTES:
        Set current to proc current_token from parser
        Set type_name to proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_BYTES
        Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, type_name
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRING_KW:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRING_KW
        Return proc create_node with SOL_ELEMENTARY_TYPE, "string"
    End If

    Note: Mapping type
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MAPPING:
        Return proc parse_mapping_type from parser
    End If

    Note: User-defined type or array
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set type_name to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        Let type_node be proc create_node with SOL_USER_DEFINED_TYPE, type_name

        Note: Check for array brackets
        While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET

            Note: Check for array size
            Let size be ""
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER:
                Set size to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER
            End If

            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET

            Let array_node be proc create_node with SOL_ARRAY_TYPE, ""
            proc set_metadata with array_node, "element_type", type_node
            proc set_metadata with array_node, "size", size
            Set type_node to array_node
        End While

        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Unknown type
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `mapping(<KeyType> => <ValueType>)`. Mappings are Solidity's
storage-only associative arrays. The `=>` arrow is lexed as a keyword
token rather than a punctuation symbol, so consume_keyword is used to
advance past it. Key and value types are stored as metadata rather than
children so HIR translation can look them up by role.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_mapping_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MAPPING
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Let key_type be proc parse_type from parser

    proc consume_keyword with parser, "=>"

    Let value_type be proc parse_type from parser

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    Let mapping_node be proc create_node with SOL_MAPPING_TYPE, ""
    proc set_metadata with mapping_node, "key_type", key_type
    proc set_metadata with mapping_node, "value_type", value_type

    Return mapping_node
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATEMENT PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for Solidity statements: if, while, for, do-while, return,
break, continue, emit, revert, try, brace blocks, and expression
statements. break/continue are handled inline because they are single-
keyword statements; everything else delegates. Expression statements are
the catch-all when no keyword matches.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: If statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IF:
        Return proc parse_if_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: While loop
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_WHILE:
        Return proc parse_while_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: For loop
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FOR:
        Return proc parse_for_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Do-while loop
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DO:
        Return proc parse_do_while_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Return statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURN:
        Return proc parse_return_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Break statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_BREAK:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_BREAK
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return proc create_node with SOL_BREAK_STMT, ""
    End If

    Note: Continue statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONTINUE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CONTINUE
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return proc create_node with SOL_CONTINUE_STMT, ""
    End If

    Note: Emit statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EMIT:
        Return proc parse_emit_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Revert statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_REVERT:
        Return proc parse_revert_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Try-catch statement
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_TRY:
        Return proc parse_try_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Block
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE:
        Return proc parse_block from parser
    End If

    Note: Expression statement
    Return proc parse_expression_statement from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `{ statement* }` as a SOL_BLOCK_STMT. Statements are appended as
ordered children. Empty blocks are legal and produce a child-less
SOL_BLOCK_STMT. Loop exits when the closing brace is seen or the parser
runs out of tokens (unclosed block defensively returns whatever was
collected).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_block" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE

    Let block be proc create_node with SOL_BLOCK_STMT, ""

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE
            Return block
        End If

        Let stmt be proc parse_statement from parser
        If stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with block, stmt
        End If
    End While

    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `if (cond) then_stmt [else else_stmt]`. The condition is stored
as "condition" metadata so it can be looked up by role; the two branches
are children (then at index 0, else at index 1 if present). The
ambiguous-else problem is resolved C-style by binding `else` to the
nearest `if` because parse_statement is greedy on the next statement.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IF

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let condition be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    Let then_stmt be proc parse_statement from parser

    Let if_node be proc create_node with SOL_IF_STMT, ""
    proc set_metadata with if_node, "condition", condition
    proc add_child with if_node, then_stmt

    Note: Check for else clause
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ELSE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_ELSE
        Let else_stmt be proc parse_statement from parser
        proc add_child with if_node, else_stmt
    End If

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `while (cond) body`. Condition lives in "condition" metadata,
body is the sole child. Body may be either a single statement or a brace
block — parse_statement handles both via its own dispatch.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_WHILE

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let condition be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser

    Let while_node be proc create_node with SOL_WHILE_STMT, ""
    proc set_metadata with while_node, "condition", condition
    proc add_child with while_node, body

    Return while_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `do body while (cond);`. The trailing semicolon after the closing
paren distinguishes do-while from a misplaced `while` after a standalone
do — Solidity requires it. Body runs at least once; condition is checked
after each iteration.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_do_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DO

    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_WHILE
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
    Let condition be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON

    Let do_while_node be proc create_node with SOL_DO_WHILE_STMT, ""
    proc set_metadata with do_while_node, "condition", condition
    proc add_child with do_while_node, body

    Return do_while_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses C-style `for (init; cond; update) body`. All three header
clauses are optional — an empty clause is recorded as 0 in the
corresponding metadata slot. Init is parsed as an expression statement
(so it can be a declaration with `=`), condition as a plain expression,
update as a plain expression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each header slot, peeks for the immediate `;` or `)`; if present,
consumes it and leaves the slot at 0, otherwise calls the appropriate
sub-parser and consumes the trailing separator. The body comes from
parse_statement after the closing paren.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_for_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FOR
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Note: Parse init (can be empty)
    Let init be 0
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Otherwise:
        Set init to proc parse_expression_statement from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse condition (can be empty)
    Let condition be 0
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Otherwise:
        Set condition to proc parse_expression from parser
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    End If

    Note: Parse update (can be empty)
    Let update be 0
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    Otherwise:
        Set update to proc parse_expression from parser
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
    End If

    Let body be proc parse_statement from parser

    Let for_node be proc create_node with SOL_FOR_STMT, ""
    proc set_metadata with for_node, "init", init
    proc set_metadata with for_node, "condition", condition
    proc set_metadata with for_node, "update", update
    proc add_child with for_node, body

    Return for_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `return [expression];`. The value is optional — `return;` is
valid for void-returning functions and is encoded as a return node with
no "value" metadata. Any value expression goes into "value" metadata
rather than as a child for symmetry with break/continue (which are also
SOL_*_STMT nodes with no children).
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_return_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURN

    Let return_node be proc create_node with SOL_RETURN_STMT, ""

    Note: Parse return value if present
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return return_node
    End If

    Let value be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc set_metadata with return_node, "value", value
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON

    Return return_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `emit <EventCall(args)>;`. The call expression is the sole child
of the emit statement. This isolates the event invocation under a
discriminator that HIR translation can use to lower into EVM LOG opcodes
rather than the regular CALL machinery.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_emit_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EMIT

    Let emit_node be proc create_node with SOL_EMIT_STMT, ""

    Let call_expr be proc parse_call_expression from parser
    proc add_child with emit_node, call_expr

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return emit_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `revert [ErrorName(args)];` — either bare (revert with no
information) or with a custom error call attached. The call form is
detected by an immediately following identifier; otherwise the revert is
recorded child-less and HIR translation emits an empty-data revert
instruction.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_revert_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_REVERT

    Let revert_node be proc create_node with SOL_REVERT_STMT, ""

    Note: Revert can have an error call or just a message
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let call_expr be proc parse_call_expression from parser
        proc add_child with revert_node, call_expr
    End If

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return revert_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `try <ExternalCall>(args) [returns (params)] { body } catch [Name]
(params) { body } ...`. The try expression is stored as "expression"
metadata. Return-binding params (if `returns` present) and the try body
become children, followed by one or more catch clauses appended by
parse_catch_clauses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `try`, parses the call as an expression. If `returns` follows,
consumes parameter list and stores each parsed parameter as a child. The
try body is parsed via parse_block and added as a child. Catch clauses
are delegated to parse_catch_clauses which keeps appending until no
TOKEN_CATCH remains.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_try_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_TRY

    Let try_node be proc create_node with SOL_TRY_STMT, ""

    Note: Parse try expression (function call)
    Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
    proc set_metadata with try_node, "expression", expr

    Note: Parse returns clause if present
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURNS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RETURNS
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

        Note: Parse return variables
        While proc not_at_end from parser:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                Let try_body be proc parse_block from parser
                proc add_child with try_node, try_body
                proc parse_catch_clauses with parser, try_node
                Return try_node
            End If

            Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
            If param is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with try_node, param
            End If

            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Set try_body to proc parse_block from parser
    proc add_child with try_node, try_body

    Note: Parse catch clauses
    proc parse_catch_clauses with parser, try_node

    Return try_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accumulator for one or more catch clauses on a try statement. Each catch
becomes a SOL_CATCH_CLAUSE child appended to try_node. Solidity permits
multiple catches per try (typed catches: `catch Error(string memory r)`
and the unnamed catch-all). The error name is captured as an optional
parameter inside the catch parenthesised list.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_catch_clauses" takes parser as Integer, try_node as Integer:
    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CATCH:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_CATCH

        Let catch_node be proc create_node with SOL_CATCH_CLAUSE, ""

        Note: Parse catch parameter if present
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

            Note: Can have error name or be empty
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
                Let param be proc parse_parameter from parser
                proc add_child with catch_node, param
            End If

            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
        End If

        Let catch_body be proc parse_block from parser
        proc add_child with catch_node, catch_body

        proc add_child with try_node, catch_node
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wraps an expression in a SOL_EXPRESSION_STMT and requires a trailing
semicolon. This thin wrapper distinguishes expressions used for side
effects (function calls, assignments) from expressions used as values
inside other constructs.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_expression_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON

    Let stmt be proc create_node with SOL_EXPRESSION_STMT, ""
    proc add_child with stmt, expr

    Return stmt
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION PARSING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point for the operator-precedence chain. Solidity expression
precedence (low to high) is: ternary → logical-or → logical-and →
equality → comparison → additive → multiplicative → unary → postfix →
primary. This single-call indirection exists so all callers route into
the chain through one fixed name even if intermediate levels are
reordered.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc parse_ternary from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ternary `cond ? then : else`. Lowest-precedence expression layer below
explicit assignment. Right-associative — `a ? b : c ? d : e` parses as
`a ? b : (c ? d : e)` because the else branch recurses through
parse_expression rather than parse_logical_or.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_ternary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr be proc parse_logical_or from parser

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_QUESTION

        Let then_expr be proc parse_expression from parser

        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COLON

        Let else_expr be proc parse_expression from parser

        Let ternary be proc create_node with SOL_TERNARY_EXPR, ""
        proc set_metadata with ternary, "condition", expr
        proc set_metadata with ternary, "then", then_expr
        proc set_metadata with ternary, "else", else_expr

        Return ternary
    End If

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Left-associative `||`. Each iteration folds the running `left` and a
freshly-parsed RHS into a new SOL_BINARY_EXPR with operator "||". Solidity
short-circuits || at runtime; the AST records both operands and HIR
translation emits the SC branch.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_logical_or" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_logical_and from parser

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_OR:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_OR
        Let right be proc parse_logical_and from parser

        Let binary be proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, "||"
        proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
        proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
        Set left to binary
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Left-associative `&&`. Same fold pattern as parse_logical_or but binds
tighter, so `a || b && c` parses as `a || (b && c)`. Short-circuit
semantics preserved by HIR translation, not by the parser.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_logical_and" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_equality from parser

    While proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_AND:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_AND
        Let right be proc parse_equality from parser

        Let binary be proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, "&&"
        proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
        proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
        Set left to binary
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Left-associative `==` and `!=`. Both have identical precedence so the
loop accepts either inside the same iteration. Loop terminates by
returning left when neither equality token appears next.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_equality" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_comparison from parser

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL
            Let right be proc parse_comparison from parser

            Let binary be proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, "=="
            proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
            proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
            Set left to binary
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL
                Set right to proc parse_comparison from parser

                Set binary to proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, "!="
                proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
                proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
                Set left to binary
            Otherwise:
                Return left
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Left-associative `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`. All four occupy the same
precedence class. Operator-token-to-operator-string mapping captured in
local `op` then used uniformly to build the SOL_BINARY_EXPR — keeps the
node-build code identical across the four cases.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_comparison" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_additive from parser

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Let op be ""

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LESS_THAN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LESS_THAN
            Set op to "<"
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL
                Set op to "<="
            Otherwise:
                If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_THAN:
                    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_THAN
                    Set op to ">"
                Otherwise:
                    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL:
                        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL
                        Set op to ">="
                    Otherwise:
                        Return left
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Let right be proc parse_additive from parser

        Let binary be proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
        proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
        Set left to binary
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Left-associative `+` and `-`. Multiplicative recursion happens through
parse_multiplicative so `a + b * c` correctly groups as `a + (b * c)`
even though both are left-associative at their own precedence level.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_additive" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_multiplicative from parser

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Let op be ""

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PLUS
            Set op to "+"
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MINUS
                Set op to "-"
            Otherwise:
                Return left
            End If
        End If

        Let right be proc parse_multiplicative from parser

        Let binary be proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
        proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
        Set left to binary
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Left-associative `*`, `/`, `%`, `**`. Solidity treats `**` at the same
multiplicative precedence as `*` rather than putting it higher — this
matches the official grammar even though most languages give exponentiation
higher precedence. Loop builds SOL_BINARY_EXPR nodes for each operator
found.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_multiplicative" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_unary from parser

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Let op be ""

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STAR:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STAR
            Set op to "*"
        Otherwise:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SLASH:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_SLASH
                Set op to "/"
            Otherwise:
                If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT:
                    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT
                    Set op to "%"
                Otherwise:
                    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_POWER:
                        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_POWER
                        Set op to "**"
                    Otherwise:
                        Return left
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Let right be proc parse_unary from parser

        Let binary be proc create_node with SOL_BINARY_EXPR, op
        proc set_metadata with binary, "left", left
        proc set_metadata with binary, "right", right
        Set left to binary
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Prefix unary operators (`!`, `-`, `++`, `--`, `delete`) and the `new`
expression. Right-associative — each operator recursively calls
parse_unary so `--!x` correctly groups as `--(!x)`. Increment and
decrement record a "prefix"="true" metadata flag so HIR translation can
distinguish prefix vs postfix forms (postfix lives in parse_postfix).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If first token is `new`, delegates immediately to parse_new_expression.
Otherwise matches each unary token and wraps the recursive result in a
SOL_UNARY_EXPR. The recursive parse_unary call rather than parse_postfix
is what gives right-associativity. If no unary leads, falls through to
parse_postfix.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_unary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unary operators
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_NOT:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_NOT
        Let operand be proc parse_unary from parser

        Let unary be proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "!"
        proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", operand
        Return unary
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_MINUS
        Set operand to proc parse_unary from parser

        Set unary to proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "-"
        proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", operand
        Return unary
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INCREMENT:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INCREMENT
        Set operand to proc parse_unary from parser

        Set unary to proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "++"
        proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", operand
        proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", "true"
        Return unary
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DECREMENT:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DECREMENT
        Set operand to proc parse_unary from parser

        Set unary to proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "--"
        proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", operand
        proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", "true"
        Return unary
    End If

    Note: Delete operator
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DELETE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DELETE
        Set operand to proc parse_unary from parser

        Set unary to proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "delete"
        proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", operand
        Return unary
    End If

    Note: New expression
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NEW:
        Return proc parse_new_expression from parser
    End If

    Return proc parse_postfix from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Postfix operations layered onto a primary expression: `.member` member
access, `[index]` array/mapping indexing, `(args)` function call, and
trailing `++`/`--` (recorded with "prefix"="false" metadata). All four
forms can chain: `obj.field[i](x)++` is one continuous postfix chain that
ends only when no further postfix token is seen.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop wraps the running `expr` in successive SOL_MEMBER_EXPR /
SOL_INDEX_EXPR / SOL_CALL_EXPR / SOL_UNARY_EXPR nodes as long as the
next token is `.`, `[`, `(`, `++`, or `--`. Object/index/function are
stored as metadata on the new node and the call-argument list is built
as ordered children of the SOL_CALL_EXPR.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_postfix" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr be proc parse_primary from parser

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        Note: Member access
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DOT:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DOT
            Let member_name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

            Let member be proc create_node with SOL_MEMBER_EXPR, member_name
            proc set_metadata with member, "object", expr
            Set expr to member
        Otherwise:
            Note: Array index
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET
                Let index be proc parse_expression from parser
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET

                Let index_expr be proc create_node with SOL_INDEX_EXPR, ""
                proc set_metadata with index_expr, "object", expr
                proc set_metadata with index_expr, "index", index
                Set expr to index_expr
            Otherwise:
                Note: Function call
                If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
                    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

                    Let call be proc create_node with SOL_CALL_EXPR, ""
                    proc set_metadata with call, "function", expr

                    Note: Parse arguments
                    While proc not_at_end from parser:
                        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                            Set expr to call
                            Let continue_flag be 1
                            Let break_flag be 1
                        End If

                        If break_flag is equal to 1:
                            Set break_flag to 0
                        Otherwise:
                            Let arg be proc parse_expression from parser
                            proc add_child with call, arg

                            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
                            End If
                        End If
                    End While

                    If continue_flag is equal to 1:
                        Set continue_flag to 0
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Postfix increment/decrement
                        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INCREMENT:
                            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_INCREMENT

                            Let unary be proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "++"
                            proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", expr
                            proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", "false"
                            Set expr to unary
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DECREMENT:
                                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_DECREMENT

                                Set unary to proc create_node with SOL_UNARY_EXPR, "--"
                                proc set_metadata with unary, "operand", expr
                                proc set_metadata with unary, "prefix", "false"
                                Set expr to unary
                            Otherwise:
                                Return expr
                            End If
                        End If
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                    Return expr
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standalone call parser used by emit and revert statements where the
caller must always be an identifier (event or error name). Differs from
the call form in parse_postfix because the name itself becomes the node
value rather than a separate "function" metadata pointer — these
statements need to inspect the named target directly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_call_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

    Let call be proc create_node with SOL_CALL_EXPR, name

    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

    Note: Parse arguments
    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
            Return call
        End If

        Let arg be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with call, arg

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    Return call
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `new <TypeName>[(args)]` — creates a fresh contract instance or
dynamic array. The constructor argument list is optional (some types
need none). Type name lives in the node value; arguments are ordered
children. Contract `new` deploys a child contract; array `new` allocates
storage.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_new_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NEW

    Let type_name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

    Let new_expr be proc create_node with SOL_NEW_EXPR, type_name

    Note: Check for constructor arguments
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN

        While proc not_at_end from parser:
            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
                Return new_expr
            End If

            Let arg be proc parse_expression from parser
            proc add_child with new_expr, arg

            If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Return new_expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bottom layer of the expression-precedence chain. Produces a leaf node
for every kind of atomic expression: number/string/hex/boolean literals,
plain identifiers, parenthesised sub-expressions, array literals, and
`payable(addr)` casts. Anything not matched returns 0 to allow callers to
detect a parse-failure cheaply.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Token-driven if-cascade matching the literal/identifier/paren/bracket/
payable token kinds. Parenthesised expressions re-enter parse_expression
to give the inside its own precedence climb. The `payable(...)` form
wraps its argument in a SOL_PAYABLE_EXPR distinct from a regular call so
HIR translation can lower it to an address-conversion cast.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_primary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Number literal
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER:
        Let value be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER
        Return proc create_node with SOL_NUMBER_LITERAL, value
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Set value to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_STRING
        Return proc create_node with SOL_STRING_LITERAL, value
    End If

    Note: Hex literal
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_HEX_LITERAL:
        Set value to proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_HEX_LITERAL
        Return proc create_node with SOL_HEX_LITERAL, value
    End If

    Note: Boolean literals
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_TRUE
        Return proc create_node with SOL_BOOLEAN_LITERAL, "true"
    End If

    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_FALSE
        Return proc create_node with SOL_BOOLEAN_LITERAL, "false"
    End If

    Note: Identifier
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name be proc expect with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
        Return proc create_node with SOL_IDENTIFIER, name
    End If

    Note: Parenthesized expression
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
        Let expr be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN
        Return expr
    End If

    Note: Array literal
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
        Return proc parse_array_literal from parser
    End If

    Note: Type cast or payable
    If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PAYABLE:
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_PAYABLE
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN
        Set expr to proc parse_expression from parser
        proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN

        Let payable_expr be proc create_node with SOL_PAYABLE_EXPR, ""
        proc set_metadata with payable_expr, "expression", expr
        Return payable_expr
    End If

    Note: Unknown primary expression
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `[expr, expr, ...]` as a SOL_ARRAY_LITERAL with elements as
ordered children. Empty array literals (`[]`) are legal and produce a
child-less node. Trailing commas are tolerated because the loop accepts
either a closing bracket or a comma after each element.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_array_literal" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET

    Let array_lit be proc create_node with SOL_ARRAY_LITERAL, ""

    While proc not_at_end from parser:
        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET
            Return array_lit
        End If

        Let element be proc parse_expression from parser
        proc add_child with array_lit, element

        If proc check with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
            proc consume with parser, SolidityLexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        End If
    End While

    Return array_lit
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST NODE UTILITIES
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single allocation site for ASTNode. Children and metadata lists are
created upfront (not lazily) because nearly every Solidity AST node
accumulates at least one child or one metadata entry, so the optimisation
of deferring list creation does not pay off here.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_node" takes node_type as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be a value of type ASTNode with
        node_type as node_type,
        value as value,
        children as proc list_create from ListCore,
        metadata as proc list_create from ListCore

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Order-preserving append onto the children list. Source order is
significant for statements inside blocks, parameters in lists, and array
literal elements — list_append maintains insertion order.
@End Reasoning

Process called "add_child" takes node as ASTNode, child as Integer:
    proc list_append from ListCore with node.children, child
End Process

@Reasoning:
Flat encoding of metadata: append key then value as two consecutive list
entries. Lookup by key is a linear scan over even indices, which is fine
because per-node metadata count is small (rarely more than 4-5 entries).
Avoids the per-node overhead of a dictionary while preserving key/value
semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two list_append calls in sequence — first key, then value. Even-indexed
entries are keys, odd-indexed entries are the matching values. This is
the storage convention; consumers iterate in pairs.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_metadata" takes node as ASTNode, key as Integer, value as Integer:
    Note: Store metadata as key-value pairs using flat list encoding
    Note: Keys at even indices (0, 2, 4...), values at odd indices (1, 3, 5...)
    Note: This avoids separate dictionary overhead while maintaining key-value semantics
    proc list_append from ListCore with node.metadata, key
    proc list_append from ListCore with node.metadata, value
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PARSER UTILITIES
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Position-indexed access to the current token. Wraps list_get so the
storage representation can later change (e.g. cached pointer array) by
editing this single function rather than every call site.
@End Reasoning

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc list_get from ListCore with parser.tokens, parser.position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming type predicate with explicit bounds guard. The
position-vs-length check happens FIRST so that solidity_token_type cannot
be called on an out-of-bounds index (which would dereference invalid
memory in ListCore). Returns 0 cleanly at or past end-of-stream.
@End Reasoning

Process called "check" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If parser.position is greater than or equal to parser.length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current be proc current_token from parser
    Let current_type be proc solidity_token_type from SolidityLexer with current

    If current_type is equal to token_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Increments the cursor by 1 unless already at end-of-stream, then returns
the new current token. Returns-the-new-token semantics let callers
chain `let next be proc advance ...` without a follow-up
current_token call.
@End Reasoning

Process called "advance" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    If parser.position is less than parser.length:
        Set parser.position to parser.position plus 1
    End If

    Return proc current_token from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Soft consume — if the current token matches, advance; otherwise leave
position untouched without raising an error. Used at sites where the
token presence is already known (called right after a successful check).
@End Reasoning

Process called "consume" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer:
    Let matches be proc check with parser, token_type
    If matches is equal to 1:
        proc advance from parser
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Like consume but matches by lexeme equality instead of by token type.
Used for Solidity tokens the lexer emits generically (e.g. `for` in using
directives or `=>` in mapping types) where the keyword identity must be
verified.
@End Reasoning

Process called "consume_keyword" takes parser as Integer, keyword as Integer:
    Let current be proc current_token from parser
    Let value be proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current

    Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with value, keyword
    If matches is equal to 1:
        proc advance from parser
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Captures the current token's lexeme value AND consumes the token. Used
when the parser needs both the lexeme (to store as a node value/name)
and the advance — combining them into one call removes a class of bugs
where one was forgotten.
@End Reasoning

Process called "expect" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let current be proc current_token from parser
    Let value be proc solidity_token_value from SolidityLexer with current

    proc consume with parser, token_type

    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
End-of-stream test with two exit conditions: position has reached the
cached length OR the current token's type is TOKEN_EOF. Both checks are
required because a well-formed token stream ends with an EOF sentinel
while a malformed truncated stream may not.
@End Reasoning

Process called "not_at_end" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    If parser.position is greater than or equal to parser.length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current be proc current_token from parser
    Let token_type be proc solidity_token_type from SolidityLexer with current

    If token_type is equal to SolidityLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public top-level alias matching the naming convention shared by sibling
frontends. Lets external callers stay decoupled from the internal
parse_solidity_source name.
@End Reasoning

Process called "solidity_parse" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc parse_solidity_source from source
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor exposing the SOL_* discriminant to HIR translation passes that
cannot see ASTNode layout directly. Encapsulation here is important
because the struct's field order may change for cache locality without
breaking external consumers.
@End Reasoning

Process called "solidity_ast_type" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.node_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the leaf-node lexeme (identifier text, operator symbol,
literal value text, type name, etc.). Returns "" for interior nodes
whose payload lives in children/metadata instead.
@End Reasoning

Process called "solidity_ast_value" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor returning the ListCore handle of the node's ordered children.
Caller walks it with list_get/list_length; the handle remains owned by
the ASTNode for lifetime purposes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "solidity_ast_children" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.children
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor returning the ListCore handle of the node's flat key/value
metadata list. Callers iterate in pairs (index i = key, index i+1 = value)
or use a helper that linearly searches by key.
@End Reasoning

Process called "solidity_ast_metadata" takes node as ASTNode returns Integer:
    Return node.metadata
End Process
